04927nam a22007575i 9780812292428DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20152016pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)952805589  a97808122924287 a10.9783/97808122924282doi  a(DE-B1597)463561  a(OCoLC)920013341  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aHV9955.P4 7aHIS0360302bisacsh04a365.42231 aManion, Jen, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLiberty's Prisoners :bCarceral Culture in Early America /cJen Manion. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2015] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (296 p.) :b10 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aEarly American Studies00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1. Rebellious Workers -- tChapter 2. Sentimental Families -- tChapter 3. Dangerous Publics -- tChapter 4. Freedom’s Limits -- tChapter 5. Sexual Orderings -- tConclusion -- tAppendix -- tNotes -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aLiberty's Prisoners examines how changing attitudes about work, freedom, property, and family shaped the creation of the penitentiary system in the United States. The first penitentiary was founded in Philadelphia in 1790, a period of great optimism and turmoil in the Revolution's wake. Those who were previously dependents with no legal standing—women, enslaved people, and indentured servants—increasingly claimed their own right to life, liberty, and happiness. A diverse cast of women and men, including immigrants, African Americans, and the Irish and Anglo-American poor, struggled to make a living. Vagrancy laws were used to crack down on those who visibly challenged longstanding social hierarchies while criminal convictions carried severe sentences for even the most trivial property crimes.The penitentiary was designed to reestablish order, both behind its walls and in society at large, but the promise of reformative incarceration failed from its earliest years. Within this system, women served a vital function, and Liberty's Prisoners is the first book to bring to life the experience of African American, immigrant, and poor white women imprisoned in early America. Always a minority of prisoners, women provided domestic labor within the institution and served as model inmates, more likely to submit to the authority of guards, inspectors, and reformers. White men, the primary targets of reformative incarceration, challenged authorities at every turn while African American men were increasingly segregated and denied access to reform.Liberty's Prisoners chronicles how the penitentiary, though initially designed as an alternative to corporal punishment for the most egregious of offenders, quickly became a repository for those who attempted to lay claim to the new nation's promise of liberty.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 7aHISTORY / United States / Revolutionary Period (1775-1800).2bisacsh  aAmerican History.  aAmerican Studies.  aGender Studies.  aWomen's Studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2015z9783110439687oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2015z9783110438635oZDB-23-DEG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Pennsylvania Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311066591840uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/978081229242840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780812292428423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780812292428.jpg  a978-3-11-066591-8  University of Pennsylvania Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS